[1] Update
Date: Fri 18 Apr 2008
From: Dolman, Sharon (MOH)
<Sharon.Dolman@ontario.ca>


Measles in Ontario -- Update to Mon 14 Apr 2008
-----------------------------------------------
As of Mon 14 Apr 2008, 6 health regions in southern Ontario, Canada,
have reported 10 cases of IgM-positive measles since 19 Mar 2008. Of
those cases, 8 are epidemiologically linked either directly to or
through a generation of cases who attended a Toronto attraction and
were exposed to the initial case in this cluster. The source of this
initial infection is not known. The 1st reported case had rash onset
on 12 Mar 2008.

One of the cases is likely imported. This person travelled from a
high incidence measles area in the middle of the incubation period.
This case is confirmed to be a different genotype (D4). Five of the
epidemiologically linked cases have been genotyped so far and were
confirmed to have infection with D8 virus. Testing for genotype
confirmation is pending for the rest of the cases. Several
investigations for other reports of rash illness are still ongoing.

The 10 cases range in age from 6 to 42 years of age. One case had a
confirmed receipt of a single dose of measles containing vaccine,
another reported two doses, and the remaining cases were completely
unimmunized.

Contact tracing and follow-up is ongoing and includes the public
potentially exposed at school settings, day nurseries, doctor
offices, a hair salon, local hospitals, retail centres, restaurants,
and a Toronto attraction.

Unimmunized or incompletely vaccinated children attending day care
were excluded from attending these centres. People attending school
had to provide proof of 2 doses of measles, mumps, and rubella (MMR)
vaccine to return. Susceptible exposed persons are being asked to
remain in self-enforced quarantine until past the maximal incubation
period and to call ahead when seeking medical assessment so that
arrangements can be made to avoid exposure of others. As per Canada's
National Advisory Committee on Immunization, persons born before 1970
and persons who have had 2 doses of measles-containing vaccine after
their 1st birthday are considered immune.

Measles is rare in Ontario. Over the last 5 years (2003 to 2007),
there were 25 cases of measles reported in Ontario. The number of
cases reported each year ranges from zero to 10 cases, with the
majority due to importation from countries with significantly higher
rates of measles.

Ontario law requires all school children to have 2 doses of measles
vaccine but children can be given exemptions on religious and
personal belief grounds. The law is less clear for children attending
day care as this is guided by recommendations from each local Medical
Officer of Health.

--
Douglas W. MacPherson, MD, MSc(CTM), FRCPC
Physician Manager
Public Health Division
Ontario Ministry of Health and Long-Term Care

and

Sharon Dolman RN, MSc
Nurse Epidemiologist
TB / Respiratory Diseases Unit
Infectious Diseases Branch
Public Health Division
Ministry of Health and Long-Term Care Ontario
5700 Yonge St. 8th floor
Toronto, ON M2M 4K5

[ProMed-mail thanks Douglas MacPherson and Sharon Dolman for
provision of this update. The presence of 2 genotypes in this
outbreak is interesting, one clearly imported and the other possibly
indigenous. - Mod.CP]

