[2] Comment
Date: Fri 18 Spr 2008
From: Ginger Switzer, ARNP, COHN-S


A comment in response to ProMED-mail Measles - Canada (02): Toronto
20080413.1341
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Thank you Professor Gold, for sharing the reasoning behind Canada's
measles vaccine policy which currently considers birth prior to 1970
as evidence for probable immunity by natural infection. With all due
respect to the Canadian public health decision makers who clearly
have far greater expertise than I do, the data reflecting the
consequences of that assumption suggest the policy might need to be
reviewed. It would appear Canada experienced a similar problem during
the measles outbreak in 1985-6 with persons who received killed
measles vaccine and no subsequent boosters as we did here in the USA
in the 1991 epidemic.

In the following data reported by the CDC, at least 29 percent of
5260 cases of measles which occurred in Canada in 1986 were in
persons born before 1970. And according to Larke in the 2nd reference
here, "During the extensive measles epidemic in Alberta in 1979, a
high proportion of the reported cases occurred in adolescents and
young adults previously vaccinated with killed vaccine, and the
majority of these developed atypical measles syndrome."

(1) International Notes Update: Measles -- Canada, 198
<http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00000737.htm>

"Age data are available for 5260 (98 percent) of the 5367 cases
reported in Canada during the 1st 2 1/2 months of 1986 (Table 4).
Thirty-six percent of cases occurred among 10- to 14-year-olds; 29
percent, among 15- to 19-year-olds; and 21 percent, among 5- to
9-year-olds. The highest incidence rate (104/100 000) occurred for
10- to 14-year-olds. The rate for 15- to 19-year-olds and 5- to
9-year-olds was 77 cases and 61 cases/100 000, respectively. In 1985,
10- to 14-year-olds also had the highest incidence rate (45/100 000).

Editorial Note: Measles vaccine of several types, including
inactivated vaccine, has been used in Canada since 1964 (1). All
provinces now routinely use further attenuated measles vaccine
combined with mumps and rubella (MMR), which is recommended for use
at or after 12 months of age (2). The mean annual measles incidence
rate decreased from 358 cases/100 000 during the prevaccine era
(1949-1958) to 30/100 000 during 1976-1985, a 92 percent reduction.
The highest rate during the past 10 years was in 1979 -- 95/100 000
in 1979. The lowest reported incidence occurred in 1983--4/100 000."

(2) Impact of measles in Canada. Author(s) Larke RP, Source Rev
Infect Dis 1983 May-Jun; 5(3):445-51.
<http://www.unboundmedicine.com/medline/ebm/record/6878997/full_citation/Impact_of_measles_in_Canada_?>

"Throughout recent years the age-specific incidence of reported cases
of measles has remained highest in the group 5 to 9 years of age, but
there has been a definite increase in the proportion of cases of
measles in persons greater than 10 years of age. During the extensive
measles epidemic in Alberta in 1979, a high proportion of the
reported cases occurred in adolescents and young adults previously
vaccinated with killed vaccine, and the majority of these developed
atypical measles syndrome."

--
Ginger Switzer, ARNP, COHN-S
EHPEC Employee Health Practitioners, Educators, and Consultants

[ProMED-mail thanks Ginger Switzer for these observations and the
documentation. - Mod.CP]
